[1] Cholera - Kenya (Siaya County)
Date: Mon 29 Feb 2016
Source: Standard Digital [edited]
http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/article/2000193311/three-die-in-siaya-as-cholera-claims-more-lives/


Another 3 people have died of cholera in [Siaya] county, raising the death toll to 8 since last week. County Public Health Officer Mabel Chanzu said 119 more cases of those infected have been reported, bringing the number of those admitted in hospital to 140. The victims have been admitted to Ambira hospital, Simenya dispensary, Rangala, and St Paul's missions' hospitals in Ugunja, while others are in Ukwala Sub-county Hospital and Sifuyo health centre in Ugenya. In Alego Usonga, patients are admitted to Siaya County Referral Hospital, Rwambwa and Rabar health centres, and Inuka Dispensary in Gem. "We are working with community health workers to help in educating the public on the importance of using treated water," said Chanzu.

The major sources of the infection are Uludhi and Wuoroya rivers that cut across the villages in Ugunja, Gem, and Alego Usonga sub-counties and River Nzoia in Ugenya. By last [Wed 24 Feb 2016], 5 people had died and 69 others were admitted to hospital after the 1st outbreak of cholera in 2016. "We are now doing door-to-door sensitisation as a way of containing the disease," she added.

Chanzu said health teams were also visiting funerals and village barazas [place where public meetings are held] to educate the public. She also added that they are working on water quality control where they distribute water treatment chemicals like pur, aqua tab, chlorine granules, and water guard. "We are educating the residents on how to use the chlorine chemicals and we allow them to demonstrate to ensure they are well educated. The people are also being advised on water, especially to avoid using a particular water source for drinking, cooking, bathing and washing," said Chanzu.

She said public health teams had put up cholera treatment units in health centres, which are well equipped to prevent and control the spread.

[Byline: Olivia Odhiambo]

