[3] Cholera - Zambia (Lusaka Province)
Date: Thu 25 Feb 2016
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited]
http://www.china.org.cn/world/Off_the_Wire/2016-02/25/content_37865831.htm


Cholera cases in Lusaka, the Zambian capital, have increased to 41 with 1 death recorded so far since the waterborne disease broke out early in February 2016, a senior government official said on [Wed 24 Feb 2016]. Ministry of Health acting spokesperson Tasila Pitters said only the death of an 18-month-old female child has been recorded so far, adding that the cumulative number of suspected cases recorded so far were 41 while confirmed laboratory positive cases were 18.

The 1st case was recorded on 4 Feb 2016 in one of the city's sprawling slums and the official said health authorities have since intensified inspection to contain the disease. So far 152 public premises, 52 schools have been inspected in the affected area and 97 water samples collected. According to the official, research conducted in the area has established that the main source of cholera was from contaminated water being used by the community.

The authorities have since distributed 15 518 bottles of chlorine so that residents could treat their water.

This is the 1st time in 6 years that the Zambian capital is experiencing a cholera outbreak.

